The '''call center industry in Bangladesh''' was worth around $12 million in 2013, of which 50 percent was accounted for by the country's domestic market.<ref name="momentum">{{cite web|author=Abdullah Mamun |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/beta2/news/call-centre-business-gains-momentum/ |title=Call centre business gains momentum |publisher=Thedailystar.net |date= |accessdate=2013-12-17}}</ref> In 2013, national mobile operators [[Airtel Bangladesh|Airtel]] and [[Citycell]] outsourced their call centers to local companies.<ref name="momentum"/> [[Bangladesh Telecommunication Regulatory Commission]] (BTRC) eased the licensing process for call centers in 2013.<ref name="momentum"/>

A call center "village" was planned in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|author=Md Hasan |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=119715 |title=Call centres on the rebound |publisher=Archive.thedailystar.net |date=2009-12-30 |accessdate=2013-12-17}}</ref> {{asof|2013}}, around 70 call centers were in operation in Bangladesh.<ref name="momentum"/> Bangladesh exports its call center services to countries including the United States, Canada and the United Kingdom.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} The [[Bangladesh Association of Call Center & Outsourcing]] (BACCO) was formed in connection with the industry.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}}

