[[Error]]s of various types may occur in [[legal proceeding]]s and may or may not constitute grounds for [[appeal (law)|appeal]].
==Types of error== * [[Harmless error]] is one considered not to have affected the trial's outcome and is thus not grounds for appeal. Harmless error is distinguished from "plain error" in that if error is "preserved"<ref>{{cite web|author1=William B. Cassel|author2=Anneliese Wright|title=Preservation of Error for Appellate Review|url=http://lawreviewbulletin.unl.edu/?p=711|publisher=Law Review Bulletin (2 Neb. L. Rev. Bull. 1)|page=711|date=2010}}</ref> by the making of a timely [[objection (law)|objection]], the [[legal burden of proof|burden of proof]] is on the [[respondent]] to show that the error was harmless, but if error was not preserved, the burden of proof is on the [[appellant]] to show that the error was plain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/rules/frcrmp/Rule52.htm |title=Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure - Rule 52 (LII 2009 ed.) |publisher=Law.cornell.edu |date= |accessdate=2010-05-16}}</ref> * [[Invited error]] is error brought about by a party's own conduct during a trial, and does not give grounds for appeal. * [[Reversible error]] is one that can lead to a judgment being overturned on appeal.
==See also== * [[Actual innocence]] * [[Fundamental error]] * [[Miscarriage of justice]] * [[Mistake of law]]
