{{Infobox language |name=Mimi-D |altname=Mimi of Decorse |nativename=Mimi of Gaudefroy-Demombynes |states=[[Chad]] |ethnicity= |extinct= (attested ca. 1900) |familycolor=Nilo-Saharan |fam2=? |iso3=none |glotto=mimi1240 |glottorefname=Mimi-Gaudefroy }}
'''Mimi of Decorse''', also known as '''Mimi of Gaudefroy-Demombynes''' and '''Mimi-D''', is a language of [[Chad]] that is attested only in a word list labelled "[[Mimi language (disambiguation)|Mimi]]" that was collected ca. 1900 by G. J. Decorse and published by Gaudefroy-Demombynes. Joseph Greenberg (1960) classified it as a [[Maban language]], like the rather remote Maban relative [[Mimi of Nachtigal]]. However, George Starostin (2011) rejects this classification, arguing that similarities to Maban are due to contact with locally dominant [[Maba language|Maba]] (the similarities are with that language specifically, not with the entire Maban family), and provisionally regards it as a language isolate, though it is suggestive of [[Central Sudanic]].<ref>Starostin, George. [https://rggu.academia.edu/GeorgeStarostin/Papers/983014/On_Mimi On Mimi], Journal of Language Relationship, v. 6, 2011, pp. 115-140.</ref>
The more stable of Mimi-D and Mimi-N's attested vocabulary is as follows:
